<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">*sigh*
<br />

<br />
There was confusion. No one could tell me how much EXP an AA point cost at each level, or how many AA points it took to gain a level.
<br />

<br />
SO...
<br />

<br />
I decided to FIND OUT FOR MYSELF!!
<br />

<br />
I un-dinged to 50 (I'd been doing that anyway, solo'ing at level 51 with crappy gear pre-Luclin was HARD) and then re-dinged.
<br />

<br />
Turned AA exp to 50% and leveled.
<br />

<br />
Ding!
<br />
Plink! (aa-ding)
<br />

<br />
Thus it is proved that level 51 --> level 52 == 1 AA
<br />

<br />
Period.
<br />

<br />
Then for every following level I spent 20% of each level putting 50% into AA exp.
<br />

<br />
Here is the chart for what each level costs in AA points. ("How many AA points worth of EXP does it take to fill the level bar and ding to the next level if I am Level Q?")
<br />

<br />
51 = 1 AA (exactly)
<br />
52 = 1.5 aa
<br />
53 = 1.5 aa
<br />
54 = 2.5 aa (first hell level)
<br />
55 = 3 aa
<br />
56 = 3 aa
<br />
57 = 3 aa (closer to 3.125 but who's counting)
<br />
58 = 3.5 aa
<br />
59 = 4 aa (second hell level)
<br />
60 = 2.5 aa (yes, 59 -is- harder than 60)
<br />
61 = 4.5 aa (nope, 61's harder than 59)
<br />
62 = 5 aa
<br />
63 = 5 aa
<br />
64 = 5.5 aa
<br />
65 = 6 aa
<br />

<br />
I do not have, and won't be getting soon, Omens so I don't have data on levels 66 - 70.
<br />

<br />
Now... when should you begin buying AAs instead of exp levels.
<br />

<br />
Buy RUN-3!! Slap 10% into AA exp and buy it. You won't regret it.
<br />

<br />
Then level like a fiend until 65 (?_70_?)
<br />

<br />
Then ask 10 different enchanters for the "one true AA path" ....
<br />

<br />
You'll get 12 (or more) answers.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
